1-14-22 Comments by Brandon Matheny;
“This could be a species that is common but undescribed on the west coast from BC to CA that has been variably labeled on GenBank as xanthomelas, mixtilis, praetervisa. If it is, then it is closely related to but distinct from European I. krieglsteineri. I would have to check my notes at home to see if your spore measurements and cystidial features are consistent with my PBM3050 (on GenBank as “praetervisa”). The pleuro are rather long.

Did the specimens turn ashy gray or blackish gray after drying?

We don’t have true xanthomelas in N.A. or have some strongly divergent populations of it that occur in eastern states and provinces ranging from Quebec to North Carolina. What Grund and Stuntz published as xanthomelas from Nova Scotia is definitely not European xanthomelas. Atkinson’s nigrescens is a possibility for it, or it will need a new name.

Compare your collection to I. phaeocystidiosa, a European species that does occur out west under conifers (I’ve sequenced it from Washington and Idaho, and it also has been sequenced from Alaska, Colorado, and Wyoming) and has been referred to as I. praetervisa, salicis-herbaceae, and hirculus (all misapplied, of course)".

results.notes:
Growing near urban highway on living, introduced tree Pterocarpus indicus (Fabaceae). Context zonate, homogenous, brown (dark brown near attachment). No resinous bands observed in the lateral section of pileus I dissected. Context rather spongy, cuticle compressible. Basidiome somewhat heavy. Cuticle cells inamyloid to faintly apically amyloid, irregular to clavate with broad resinous apex. The only spores observed were from the trama, and they seemed to be of variable maturity. Most were smaller, but sometimes reaching the dimensions in literature (G. tuberculosum). No chlamydospores seen.

—

results.notes:
Growing from dead angiosperm tree used as trail marker (see photos). Context thin, richly colored, almost duplex, dark brown near tubes and yellow brown near cuticle, resinous band present, stronger near attachment. Cuticle dull (specimens old) with shiny areas of margin suggesting sect. Ganoderma, compressible, cracking fairly easily. Cuticle cells obscure by their apparent nature of being fused together, irregular, inamyloid, intricately bound and not neatly arranged in a row such as G. subamboinense. Apex of cells clavate but not swelling to large diameter as in G. tuberculosum, stratified wax layers visible in some. A yellowish pigment extractable from sections of cuticle in KOH, possibly just the diffusion of deposited spores. Spores 9×6um.

results.notes:
Macro: Thallus whitish, continuous areolate. Areoles angular. Areoles with apothecia slightly raised above rest of thallus. Apothecia vary in shape from round to long and angular. Aps immersed and white-pruinose. Largest ap observed with average diam of ~0.5 mm. Ap margins “striated” with cracks. Margins often slightly raised above plane of areole. Pycnidia: present, black.

Micro: Apothecia: epihymenium dark brown at very top, underlain by olive green. Spores X per ascus (counted 4 in only ascus I saw w/ spores, but the 2-6 spores path in Nash 2007 doesn’t go anywhere plausible-sounding). Conidia (3 measured): 14, 16, and 17 um long. Paraphyses moniliform, coherent in H2O. Spores: 2 measured: 26.4 × 15.2 um, 25.7 × 16.4 um. Spores hyaline, ovoid.

Thallus K+Y (spot test and in section). Epihymenium K+brown. Thallus section weakly K+R (norstictic acid) in some sections. Hymenium I+ blue

Growing from standing angiosperm log in disturbed forest near stream. Pores about 6-8/mm. Pilei reduced and never well formed from other examples I’ve seen, imbricate. Skeletal hyphae of trama conpicuously encrusted, no cystidia or clamps identified. Globose elements present in hymenium appear to basidioles. Spores ellipsoid, about 5×3, hyaline in H20. Large and small rounded, free crystals appear to be present in hymenium (h20). Elements inamyloid. Globose, yellowish slightly thick walled and faintly echinulate chlamydospores may be present in context (artifact?). Skeletal hyphae dominant in context, long, unbranched, interwoven. No clamps or septa observed (generative hyphae not observed).

Stipes: white and mostly cylindrical, with orange-yellow blotching at base
KOH: bright orange on stipe
Spores: white
Habitat: mixed conifer forest, mostly Douglas-fir and Redwood, possibly some hemlock. Wet shady forest near a small gulch; understory mostly comprised of ferns near location
Odor: Sweet smell of moderate strength, recalling Cuphophyllus pratensis or Clitocybe fragrans.
Taste: weak, mild
